[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(7) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Consider what I say; and the Lord give thee understanding in all things.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The older authorities read here ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "will give;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also instead of “and the Lord,” the translation should be, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for the Lord.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Thus the sentence should run: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "will give thee understanding in all things.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Some difficulty has been found in explaining exactly why, when we look at the foregoing words, Timothy should be so specially charged to consider St. Paul’s words here, and why the declaration respecting “understanding in all things” was made in this particular place. Theophylact suggested because the preceding exhortations were in the form of metaphors, “he spake all things in an enigmatical form:” but surely these metaphors were the reverse of obscure, and did not seem to need for their comprehension any special enlightenment; if then we refer the words of this verse exclusively to what precedes, it will be best to understand the charge of St. Paul, “Consider what I say,” &c., as directing Timothy’s attention to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "personal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " application of each of the pictures, or metaphors. It seems, however, that the words “Consider,” &c., while referring to what he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "had",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " said, belong also to the far weightier words he was about to write in the next sentence (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Timothy 2:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He is in this chapter exhorting Timothy to be strong in the faith in the face of many troubles. He has instanced to him earthly examples to show how success, even ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "here, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "depends on enduring perseverance, and is now passing on to set before him other and far higher inducements for him “to be strong;” and between the first set of arguments and the second he bids him “Consider what I say” (part has been said, but yet other and deeper things are to follow). God will five him power to grasp their meaning in all their depth.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2:1-7 As our trials increase, we need to grow stronger in that which is good; our faith stronger, our resolution stronger, our love to God and Christ stronger. This is opposed to our being strong in our own strength. All Christians, but especially ministers, must be faithful to their Captain, and resolute in his cause. The great care of a Christian must be to please Christ. We are to strive to get the mastery of our lusts and corruptions, but we cannot expect the prize unless we observe the laws. We must take care that we do good in a right manner, that our good may not be spoken evil of. Some who are active, spend their zeal about outward forms and doubtful disputations. But those who strive lawfully shall be crowned at last. If we would partake the fruits, we must labour; if we would gain the prize, we must run the race. We must do the will of God, before we receive the promises, for which reason we have need of patience. Together with our prayers for others, that the Lord would give them understanding in all things, we must exhort and stir them up to consider what they hear or read.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Consider what I say; - see the notes at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 4:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The sense is \"Think of the condition of the soldier, and the principles on which he is enlisted; think of the aspirant for the crown in the Grecian games; think of the farmer, patiently toiling in the prospect of the distant harvest; and then go to your work with a similar spirit.\" These things are worth attention. When the minister of the gospel thinks of his hardships, of his struggles against an evil world, and of his arduous and constant discouraging toil, let him think of the soldier, of the man who struggles for this world's honors, and of the patient farmer - AND be content. How patiently do they bear all, and yet for what inferior rewards!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And the Lord give thee understanding in all things - Enable you to see the force of these considerations, and to apply them to your own case. Such are often the discouragements of the ministry; so prone is the mind to despondency, that we need the help of the Lord to enable us to apply the most obvious considerations, and to derive support from the most plain and simple truths and promises. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And the Lord give thee understanding in all things - Enable you to see the force of these considerations, and to apply them to your own case. Such are often the discouragements of the ministry; so prone is the mind to despondency, that we need the help of the Lord to enable us to apply the most obvious considerations, and to derive support from the most plain and simple truths and promises. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "7. Consider the force of the illustrations I have given from the soldier, the contender in the games, and the husbandmen, as applying to thyself in thy ministry.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and the Lord give, &c.—The oldest manuscripts read, \"for the Lord will give thee understanding.\" Thou canst understand my meaning so as personally to apply it to thyself; for the Lord will give thee understanding when thou seekest it from Him \"in all things.\" Not intellectual perception, but personal appropriation of the truths metaphorically expressed, was what he needed to be given him by the Lord.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
